body:
@ajweiss: Right. Xorin IP addresses might swap addresses to be within a private range like 10.x.x.x. But there i still think they will be transferred through DNS (IMO there is no DNS policy that says you can can't rely IPs in private ranges).
But even when a IP in a private range gets removed from the response, there will be enough IPs to allow a bitcoin-client to get a reasonable connection to the P2P net.
On the other hand it would be possible (changing the seeders behavior) to remove xored IP in private ranges and fill up the response with xored ips which are not in private ranges.

